The glomerulus is the network of blood capillaries that sit inside of Bowman's capsule. 

As blood flows through these capillaries (fed by the afferent arteriole), it is filtered out into the capsular space. From the capsular space, it flows into the renal tubule. The filtrate continues through the nephron and eventually becomes urine. 
\pic{"url": "https://i.imgur.com/ZSqk8y0.png", "alt": "alt goes here", "maxHeight": "500"}

The filtration membrane at the glomerulus consists of three parts. 

$\textbf{1.) Fenestrated endothelium of the capillary
}$
This prevents filtration of large substances, including blood cells. 

$\textbf{2.) Basement membrane of the glomerulus
}$
This is a proteoglycan gel that is negatively charged, which helps prevent filtration of large negatively charged proteins. 

$\textbf{3.) Filtration slits between pedicels. 
}$
Pedicels are the foot processes of podocytes, which are large cells that wrap around capillaries in the glomerulus. These are also negatively charged preventing large anions and medium-sized proteins. 

\pic{"url": "https://i.imgur.com/FpL86bF.png", "alt": "alt goes here", "maxHeight": "450"}

Leukocytes are excluded from the filtrate because they are too large to pass through any part of the glomerular filtration membrane. 

Molecules less than 3 nm can typically pass through the filtration membrane. This includes small ions, glucose, and free amino acids, though some molecules may be reabsorbed further on in the nephron. 

\pic{"url": "https://i.imgur.com/SYduPQl.png", "alt": "alt goes here", "maxHeight": "450"}

The detrusor muscle is a smooth muscle layer in the wall of the urinary bladder. It's function is to contract to expel urine. 

The detrusor is under autonomic nervous control. The parasympathetic (rest and digest) nervous system stimulates the contraction of the detrusor, leading to urination. In contrast, the sympathetic (fight or flight) nervous system inhibits the detrusor, allowing the bladder to fill with urine. 

\pic{"url": "https://i.imgur.com/pWT3F0H.png", "alt": "alt goes here", "maxHeight": "400"}

Sodium (Na$^{+}$) is the most abundant cation in the extracellular fluid (ECF). Potassium (K$^{+}$), on the other hand, is the most abundant cation inside the cell (ICF)

I like to remember this concept by picturing a lone boat full of bananas out on the ocean. The boat represents the cell and the ICF, loaded with potassium. The salty water of the ocean represents the ECF. 

\pic{"url": "https://i.imgur.com/Yh4tXFk.png", "alt": "alt goes here", "maxHeight": "400"}

Antidiuretic hormone (ADH) acts on the collecting duct to increase its permeability to water by inserting aquaporins in the membrane of tubule cells. 

Aquaporins are membrane proteins that form channels for water to cross through. I like to remember the function of ADH by with the mnemonic: Always Digging Holes. The "holes" are the aquaporins. 

