During digestion, our body breaks large food molecules down into their constituent parts. 

\underline{\textbf{Option A: Carbohydrates, Glycerol}} 
Option A is not correct because glycerol is a component of lipids (fats), not carbohydrates (sugars).

\underline{\textbf{Option B: Carbohydrates, Monosaccharides}}
Option B is correct because carbohydrates are molecules made up of many individual sugars (monosaccharides) chained together. 

\underline{\textbf{Option C: Proteins, Fatty Acids}}
Option C is incorrect because proteins are broken down into amino acids, not fatty acids. Fatty acids are components of lipids. 

\underline{\textbf{Option D: Lipids, Amino Acids}}
Option D is incorrect because lipids are broken down into fatty acids and glycerol, not amino acids. Amino acids are the building block of proteins.

\underline{\textbf{Fats}}
Fats provide 9 kcal/gram of energy.

\underline{\textbf{Proteins}}
Proteins provide 4 kcal/gram of energy.

\underline{\textbf{Carbohydrates}}
Carbohydrates also provide 4 kcal/gram of energy.

\underline{\textbf{Minerals}}
This question asks specifically about macronutrients. Minerals are considered micronutrients, and don't really provide any energy.

\underline{\textbf{Enzyme A}}
We know that enzyme A is responsible for breaking down lactose. Our options for enzyme A are: dextrinase, amylase, lipase, and lactase. Of these, lactase is the only enzyme that breaks down lactose. dextrinase and amylase work on larger sugars, and lipase works on fats.

\underline{\textbf{Enzyme B}}
The enzyme responsible for breaking down starch is amylase.

\underline{\textbf{Enzyme C}}
Chymotrypsin, aminopeptidase, and pepsin all help breakdown proteins, but this question is asking about which one functions in the stomach. Of these, pepsin is the only enzyme that carries out its function in the stomach.

Oxidative De\textit{\textbf{amin}}ation is not a pathway of glucose metabolism, but is a part of amino acid metabolism. 

Aerobic respiration of glucose starts with glycolysis:

\textbf{\underline{1.) Glycolysis}}
The goal here to break down (-lysis means to break down) a glucose molecule to form pyruvate. Two molecules of pyruvate are formed for every one molecule of glucose. In aerobic conditions, the pyruvate is converted to Acetyl CoA, which enters the citric acid cycle.

\textbf{\underline{2.) Citric Acid Cycle (Krebs Cycle)}}
Here, the oxidation of glucose is completed. Energy carrying coenzymes (NADH, FADH\textsubscript{2}) and some ATP molecules are produced. 

\textbf{\underline{3.) Electron Transport Chain & Oxidative Phosphorylation}}
The coenzymes from earlier help establish a protein gradient that helps add a phosphate group to ADP to form ATP (oxidative phosphorylation). This step in the process is where most ATP is formed.

\textbf{\underline{A. Taurine / hydrolysis / protease:}}
\indent[1rem]{- Taurine is a component of bile salts, but cholesterol is the primary starting material.}
\indent[1rem]{- Hydrolysis is a general term for breaking down molecules with water.}
\indent[1rem]{- Protease is an enzyme that breaks down proteins, not fats.}

\textbf{\underline{B. Triglycerides / agglomeration / amylase:}}
\indent[1rem]{- Triglycerides are fats themselves, not a source for bile salts.}
\indent[1rem]{- Agglomeration means clumping together, while emulsification is the opposite, breaking down large particles.}
\indent[1rem]{- Amylase is an enzyme that breaks down carbohydrates, not fats.}

\textbf{\underline{C. Bilirubin / micelles formation / salivary lipase:}}
\indent[1rem]{- Bilirubin is a waste product, not a component of bile salts.}
\indent[1rem]{- Micelle formation is a correct term for the structures formed by bile salts and fat particles, but happens later in the process.}
\indent[1rem]{- Salivary lipase does fat digestion in the mouth, but pancreatic lipase is the major player in the small intestine.}

\textbf{\underline{D. Cholesterol / emulsification / pancreatic lipase:}}
\indent[1rem]{- Cholesterol is the starting material for bile salts produced by the liver.}
\indent[1rem]{- Emulsification is the process by which bile salts break down large fat globules into smaller particles.}
\indent[1rem]{- Pancreatic lipase is the key enzyme that breaks down these emulsified fats.}

\textbf{\underline{A. Micelles:}}
Micelles are complexes with a polar (hydrophilic) outer shell and non-polar (hydrophobic) inner core. Long chain fatty acids, cholesterol, and other fat-soluble, hydrophobic molecules can dissolve into this core area to be transported and absorbed. 

\textbf{\underline{B. Lipoprotein:}}
Lipoproteins carry lipids around in the blood, but not the small intestine. 

\textbf{\underline{C. Chyle:}}
Chyle is the fluid that forms in the lacteal after lipids are absorbed and mix with the lymph fluid.

\textbf{\underline{D. Globules:}}
Globules are aggregates of fat before they are broken down into smaller droplets by emulsification.

\underline{\textbf{Option A:}}
The byproducts of enzymatic digestion of triglycerides in the intestine are fatty acids and 2-monogylcerides, not LDL.

\underline{\textbf{Option B:}}
LDL is a type of lipoprotein that delivers cholesterol to the rest of the body's cells. The liver produces VLDL, which has a core packed triglycerides and cholesterol. As VLDL travels the body, it brings more triglycerides to the cells. As triglycerides are removed, VLDL becomes IDL, which becomes the cholesterol rich LDL. 

\underline{\textbf{Option C:}}
This describes lipoprotein lipase, not LDL. 

\underline{\textbf{Option D:}}
This describes a molecule involved in the breakdown of sugars (glyc/o = sugar, -lysis = breakdown), not LDL, which is a cholesterol transport molecule.

\textbf{\underline{Leptin}}
Leptin is produced by fat cells, which are the main way the body stores energy. As fat stores increase, so does leptin production. 

Leptin acts on the hypothalamus to signal satiety and decrease appetite. This is a long-term process. Essentially, increased leptin signals the brain to eat less, and the lack of leptin signals the brain to eat more. 

\textbf{\underline{Ghrelin}}
Ghrelin, also called the "hunger hormone" is produced by the stomach and stimulates hunger/appetite. Its levels rise before eating, and decrease after. It works in the short term. 

\textbf{\underline{Amylin}}
Amylin is secreted by the pancreas and functions to terminate eating and promote "fullness" (satiety). It works in the short term.

\textbf{\underline{Peptide YY}}
Peptide YY is a hormone secreted by enteroendocrine cells in the ileum and colon. Like amylin, it also signals satiety and to terminate eating. It also works in the short term.

Both the dartos and cremaster muscles help maintain the proper temperature for sperm production, but they do so in different ways. 

\underline{\textbf{Dartos}}
The dartos is a smooth muscle layer that surrounds the testes. In cold conditions, it contracts, which tightens the scrotum and helps trap heat in, which also wrinkles the scrotum, lowering the amount of surface area available for heat loss. When exposed to heat, it relaxes and allows the scrotal skin to hang looser around the testes, which helps heat loss. 

\underline{\textbf{Cremaster}}
The cremaster is a combination of skeletal and smooth muscle that raises and lowers the testes. When it's cold, it contracts to raise the testes in closer to the body heat. When it's warmer, it relaxes to allow the testes to hang further away from the body.

 Spermatogenesis takes place in the \underline{seminiferous tubules}, while the storage and maturation of sperm occur in the \underline{epididymis}.

Here's a breakdown of these two structures: 

\underline{\textbf{Seminiferous Tubules}}
These are tightly coiled tubes within the testes, where spermatogenesis (development of sperm cells) occurs.  

\underline{\textbf{Epididymis}}
Once produced, sperm cells travel through the rete testis and efferent tubules to get to the epididymis. This is where they mature and gain motility (the ability to move). 
